SIMPLE: instinct
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Instinct
<hw>In*stinct"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>instinctus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>instinguere</ets> to instigate,
incite; cf. <ets>instigare</ets> to instigate. Cf. <er>Instigate</er>,
<er>Distinguish</er>.]</ety> <def>Urged or stimulated from within;
naturally moved or impelled; imbued; animated; alive; quick; <as>as,
birds <ex>instinct</ex> with life</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The chariot of paternal deity . . . ⟦br⟧
Itself <qex>instinct</qex> with spirit, but convoyed⟦br⟧
By four cherubic shapes.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A noble performance, <qex>instinct</qex> with sound principle.</q>
<rj><qau>Brougham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Instinct</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Instinct
<hw>In"stinct</hw> <pr>(⟦icr⟧n"st⟦icr⟧⟦nsm⟧kt)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[L. <ets>instinctus</ets> instigation, impulse, fr.
<ets>instinguere</ets> to instigate: cf. F. <ets>instinct</ets>. See
<er>Instinct</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Natural inward impulse; unconscious, involuntary, or
unreasoning prompting to any mode of action, whether bodily, or mental,
without a distinct apprehension of the end or object to be
accomplished.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An <qex>instinct</qex> is a propensity prior to experience, and
independent of instructions.</q> <rj><qau>Paley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An <qex>instinct</qex> is a blind tendency to some mode of action,
independent of any consideration, on the part of the agent, of the end
to which the action leads.</q> <rj><qau>Whately.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An <qex>instinct</qex> is an agent which performs blindly and
ignorantly a work of intelligence and knowledge.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By a divine <qex>instinct</qex>, men's minds mistrust⟦br⟧
Ensuing dangers.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Specif., the natural,
unreasoning, impulse by which an animal is guided to the performance of
any action, without thought of improvement in the method.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The resemblance between what originally was a habit, and an
<qex>instinct</qex> becomes so close as not to be distinguished.</q>
<rj><qau>Darwin.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A natural aptitude or knack; a predilection; <as>as,
an <ex>instinct</ex> for order; to be modest by
<ex>instinct</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Instinct</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Instinct
<hw>In*stinct"</hw> <pr>(⟦icr⟧n*st⟦icr⟧⟦nsm⟧kt")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<def>To impress, as an animating power, or instinct.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Bentley.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Instinction</ent>⟦br⟧
